    63	lab-helper path. `--login-helper env` unsets `KEEPER_SDK_LOGIN_HELPER`
    64	for SDK subprocesses and instead exports `KEEPER_EMAIL`,
    65	`KEEPER_PASSWORD`, and `KEEPER_TOTP_SECRET` so the provider falls back
    66	to the public `EnvLoginHelper` contract. The smoke log and failure
    67	post-mortem explicitly name which auth path ran: `deploy_watcher`
    68	helper vs public `EnvLoginHelper` env path.
    69	
    70	Exit codes come from `smoke.py::main()`:
    71	
    72	| code | meaning |
    73	|------|---------|
    74	| `0` | Smoke passed, or `--teardown` completed successfully |
    75	| `2` | Interrupted run, smoke/assertion failure, or SDK command failure after cleanup was attempted |
    76	| `3` | Preflight failure before the main smoke cycle started |
    77	| `4` | Tenant or provider constraint failure, such as a missing or invisible required gateway |
    78	
    79	## What the smoke exercises
    80	
    81	- Logs in as the tenant admin with `identity.admin_login()`
    82	- Ensures the `testuser2` smoke identity exists and is usable with `identity.ensure_sdktest_identity()`
    83	- Ensures the reusable sandbox exists with `sandbox.ensure_sandbox()`: shared folder `SDK Test (ephemeral)`, KSM app `SDK Test KSM`, gateway visibility, app binding, and share to `testuser2`
    84	- Pre-cleans the sandbox with `sandbox.teardown_records(..., manager=MANAGER_NAME)` to remove orphaned SDK-managed records from prior runs
    85	- Writes a scenario-specific smoke manifest and an empty destroy manifest
    86	- Runs SDK `validate` against the generated manifest
    87	- Runs SDK `plan` and expects exit `2` because the initial plan should contain creates
    88	- Runs SDK `apply --auto-approve` to create the scenario records
    89	- Discovers live state through `CommanderCliProvider.discover()` and verifies every expected SDK-managed scenario record, including nested `pamUser` records for `pamUserNested`
    90	- Runs SDK `plan` again and expects exit `0` for a clean re-plan
    91	- After destroy apply, sweeps the project Resources and Users shared-folder
    92	  UIDs for any remaining SDK-marked records (handles ``reference_existing``
    93	  ``pam_configuration`` rows that empty-manifest plans do not always delete),
    94	  then re-discovers with an **empty** provider ``manifest_source`` so the
    95	  synthetic reference-configuration live row is not injected into the final
    96	  “no SDK-owned rows” check
    97	- Runs SDK `plan --allow-delete` against the empty manifest and expects exit `2` because deletes should be present
    98	- Runs SDK `apply --allow-delete --auto-approve` against the empty manifest
    99	- Re-discovers live state and verifies no records carrying this SDK ownership marker remain
   100	
   101	## Teardown
   102	
   103	`python3 scripts/smoke/smoke.py --teardown` runs the same auth, identity, sandbox, and pre-clean path, then stops after deleting SDK-managed records in the sandbox shared folder. The delete guard lives in `sandbox.teardown_records()`: it lists records in the target shared folder, reads each record's `keeper_declarative_manager` marker, decodes it, and deletes only records whose decoded payload has `manager == MANAGER_NAME`.
   104	
   105	## Troubleshooting
   106	
   107	| symptom | next action |
   108	|---------|-------------|
   109	| `two_factor_code_invalid` | `identity.py` retries on the next TOTP window, once per window, up to 3 attempts; if it persists, re-run with `--force` to reprovision `testuser2` TOTP state |
   110	| `keeper CLI not found on PATH` | Install `keepercommander` via `pip` so the `keeper` executable is available |
   111	| `Required gateway 'Lab GW Rocky' is not visible` | The admin session cannot see the gateway; ensure the admin `commander-config.json` belongs to a user with access, then re-run |
   112	| `Commander returned non-JSON` from `ls` on an empty folder | Already handled internally in `sandbox._loads_json()`: empty output is treated as `[]` |
   113	| Keeper subprocess commands hang | They should not hang after `--batch-mode` plus `KEEPER_PASSWORD`; if they do, check that the `testuser2` Commander config still has a valid `device_token` and `clone_code` |
   114	| SDK command failure | The post-mortem includes the full SDK command, exit code, stdout tail, and stderr tail so the parent/live runner can see Commander/provider details without rerunning blind |
   115	
   116	## Non-negotiable constraints
   117	
   118	No `keeper_dag` imports are allowed in this workflow, all tenant-side mutations must go through Commander CLI calls, the smoke must stay idempotent across reruns by reusing and pre-cleaning its sandbox, and teardown must never delete records that are not explicitly marked as SDK-managed.
   119	
   120	## Tenant state after a passing run
   121	
   122	- The shared folder `SDK Test (ephemeral)` remains in place for reuse
   123	- The KSM application `SDK Test KSM` remains in place and bound to the sandbox shared folder
   124	- The share from the sandbox shared folder to `testuser2` remains in place
   125	- All SDK-managed records created inside the sandbox shared folder during the smoke are deleted by the destroy phase
   126	
   127	## Profiles
   128	
   129	`--profile <id>` lets multiple smoke identities use disjoint shared folders,
   130	KSM apps, Commander configs, PAM project names, record-title prefixes, and TOTP
   131	channel names. The default profile is built in and preserves the historical
   132	one-command behavior:
   133	
   134	```bash
   135	python3 scripts/smoke/smoke.py --scenario pamMachine
   136	python3 scripts/smoke/smoke.py --profile p1 --scenario pamMachine
   137	python3 scripts/smoke/identity.py --profile p1
   138	```
   139	
   140	Non-default profiles are read from `scripts/smoke/profiles/<id>.json`. Real
   141	profile JSON files are gitignored; commit only `default.example.json`.
   142	
   143	```json
   144	{
   145	  "id": "p1",
   146	  "target_email": "msawczyn+sdk-p1@acme-demo.com",
   147	  "ksm_config": "/path/to/ksm-config.json",
   148	  "admin_commander_config": "/path/to/commander-config.json",
   149	  "sdktest_commander_config": "scripts/smoke/.commander-config-sdk-p1.json",
   150	  "keeper_server": "keepersecurity.com",
   151	  "channel_name": "sdk-declarative-p1",
   152	  "password": "profile-test-user-password",
   153	  "default_admin_record_uid": "ADMIN_CREDS_RECORD_UID",
   154	  "sdk_test_login_record_title": "SDK Test — sdk-p1 Login"
   155	}
   156	```
   157	
   158	Each profile needs its own active test user and Commander config path.
   159	`identity.ensure_sdktest_identity()` is profile-aware and writes the configured
   160	test-user Commander config after TOTP enrollment or reuse. `sandbox.config_for_profile()`
   161	keeps the default shared folder/app names unchanged, while non-default profiles
   162	use `SDK Test (ephemeral) <id>` and `SDK Test KSM <id>`; the gateway remains
   163	`Lab GW Rocky`.
   164	
   165	`--node <node_uid>` is accepted as smoke-side metadata for future tenant/node
   166	partitioning, but the runner does not pass it to `dsk plan` or `dsk apply`
   167	because those CLI commands do not expose `--node` yet.
   168	
   169	Marker isolation is deliberately not a profile knob. LESSON
   170	`[smoke][marker-manager-is-core-contract]` records that
   171	`MANAGER_NAME = "keeper-pam-declarative"` is a core ownership invariant; profile
   172	isolation must come from folder, project, and title scope only.
   173	
   174	## Concurrency / parallel profiles
   175	
   176	Use `--parallel-profile` only with a non-default `--profile` whose Commander
   177	config path, test user, shared folder, KSM app, and PAM project name are
   178	disjoint from other live smoke runs:
   179	
   180	```bash
   181	python3 scripts/smoke/smoke.py --parallel-profile --profile p1 --scenario pamMachine
   182	```
   183	
   184	The harness writes a JSON lock under `<repo>/.dsk-smoke-locks/`; override the
   185	directory with `DSK_SMOKE_LOCK_DIR`. The lock records only PID, UTC start time,
   186	tenant FQDN, profile id, admin Commander config path, shared-folder title, KSM
   187	app name, and project name.
   188	
   189	Dead-PID locks are removed automatically with a warning. If a lock is older
   190	than 24 hours but its PID is still alive, the run refuses with a stuck-lock
   191	message; verify no smoke process is active before deleting that file manually.
   192	Corrupt lock JSON is never guessed or repaired automatically.
   193	
   194	Marker isolation remains out of scope for profiles. LESSON
   195	`[smoke][marker-manager-is-core-contract]` is the reason: SDK ownership
   196	`MANAGER_NAME` is a core diff/delete contract, so parallel lanes isolate by
   197	folder, project, and title scope instead.

