     1	# Keeper Vault + RBI + time-bound PAM role (test environment)
     2	
     3	Minimal demo layout: **shared RBI web session** with credentials hidden via **PAM User** linkage, plus an optional **audit-alert webhook** that grants an **enterprise role** for about one minute so users can use KeeperPAM for that window.
     4	
     5	> **Scope note (2026-04-22):** This folder is **RBI + PAM only**. The Caravan fleet stack (VM gateway, VPS, Windows host, self-healing watchdogs, Hysteria/sing-box, Caravan portal) was previously interleaved here; it now lives in the workspace-level [`caravan/`](../caravan/README.md) folder with its own KSM app (`Caravan-Ops-App`) — see [`notes/caravan-segregation.md`](../notes/caravan-segregation.md). Do not add Caravan code under this tree.
     6	
     7	## Deployment model (execute everything on one target box)
     8	
     9	Use a **single machine or VM** for:
    10	
    11	1. **Keeper Commander** — Install CLI, then **log in once** as Tenant Administrator so the persistent session (e.g. `%USERPROFILE%\.keeper` on Windows) is available to the same account that runs the webhook.
    12	2. **All provisioning** — Run `create-user`, PAM/RBI records, `audit-alert`, etc. from **this host** (`keeper shell` or your batch workflow).
    13	3. **Webhook service** — Python + uvicorn on the **same host**; it invokes the **local** `keeper` binary (`KEEPER_CLI`) for `enterprise-role … --add-user` / `--remove-user`.
    14	4. **Public HTTPS** — Put ngrok, Cloudflare Tunnel, or a reverse proxy in front of the webhook port so Keeper Cloud can reach `/keeper-webhook` (not plain `localhost` from the internet).
    15	
    16	Do not split “admin Commander on laptop” and “webhook on server” unless you duplicate auth and paths; the design assumes **one automation endpoint**.
    17	
    18	## Prerequisites
    19	
    20	- **Tenant Administrator** access (Commander or Admin Console).
    21	- **Keeper Gateway** online; **PAM Configuration** for your network.
    22	- **Advanced Reporting & Alerts (ARAM)** if you use custom audit alerts with webhooks (confirm license).
    23	- **Public HTTPS URL** for the webhook (ngrok, Cloudflare Tunnel, or a VM)—Keeper Cloud cannot call `localhost`.
    24	
    25	## Interactive menu + local password file (optional)
    26	
    27	1. Copy **`config.example.json`** → **`config.local.json`** (the latter is **gitignored**).
    28	2. Edit **`config.local.json`**: set **`keeper.password`**, **`keeper.admin_email`**, **`keeper.server`** (use **`US`** for a US tenant; change only if your vault is in another region), plus **`ksm.one_time_access_token`** / **`webhook.enterprise_role_id`** as needed.
    29	3. Run:
    30	
    31	```powershell
    32	.\scripts\prompt_actions.ps1
    33	```
    34	
    35	You get a numbered menu (KSM bind, verify settings, start webhook, Commander batch login, paths). Anything missing from the file is **prompted** at runtime. For a **US account with master password only** (no SSO), menu option **4** runs Commander batch login. Create a vault record titled **Keeper Admin Login** (recommended), share it with your KSM app, and set **`ksm.keeper_admin_login_record_uid`** in **`config.local.json`** to that record’s UID (**Login** field = email, **Password** = master password). Option **4** runs **`scripts/login_commander_via_ksm.py`** and does not read the password from **`config.local.json`**. The legacy key **`ksm.commander_credentials_record_uid`** is still honored if the new key is empty. If no UID is set, option **4** falls back to **`keeper.admin_email`** / **`keeper.password`** (or prompts).
    36	
    37	## Security
    38	
    39	- Never commit `ksm-config.json`, `.env`, **`config.local.json`**, or OTATs. If an OTAT was shared in chat, **rotate it** after binding KSM.
    40	- Restrict who can reach the webhook URL; optional `WEBHOOK_BEARER_TOKEN` is supported (from env or KSM).
    41	
    42	### KSM-backed settings (optional)
    43	
    44	After `ksm-config.json` exists, you can store **role ID**, **webhook bearer**, and extra options in **one Vault record** shared with the KSM application (no secret values in `.env` except optional UIDs):
    45	
    46	| Env variable | Purpose |
    47	|--------------|---------|
    48	| `KSM_CONFIG_RECORD_UID` | If set, load fields from this record |
    49	| `KSM_CONFIG_FILE` | Path to `ksm-config.json` (default: project root) |
    50	| `KSM_FIELD_ROLE` | Field type for enterprise role ID (default: `login`) |
    51	| `KSM_FIELD_BEARER` | Field type for webhook bearer token (default: `password`) |
    52	| `KSM_FIELD_NOTES` | Field type for JSON options (default: `notes`) |
    53	
    54	**Record layout (defaults):** **Login** field = `ENTERPRISE_ROLE_ID`; **Password** = `WEBHOOK_BEARER_TOKEN` (optional); **Notes** = JSON, e.g. `{"pam_grant_seconds":60,"keeper_cli":"C:\\\\path\\\\keeper.bat","commander_dry_run":false}`.
    55	
    56	**Precedence:** Any **environment variable** set explicitly still **overrides** KSM.
    57	
    58	`/health` returns `ksm_config_loaded: true` when a `KSM_CONFIG_RECORD_UID` was supplied and the record was fetched successfully.
