     1	# Manual provisioning checklist (Tenant Administrator)
     2	
     3	Complete these on the **same machine** where you will run the webhook service (see README “Deployment model”). Use **Admin Console** and/or **Commander** while logged in as **Tenant Administrator**. Replace placeholders with your tenant’s UIDs and names.
     4	
     5	## 0. Target box readiness
     6	
     7	1. Commander installed; `keeper login` (or equivalent) completed for the admin account that will run uvicorn.
     8	2. From a shell on that box, confirm enterprise commands work (e.g. list roles or users) without opening interactive shell-only menus, or document your batch wrapper.
     9	3. Note full path to `keeper.exe` if it is not on `PATH`; set `KEEPER_CLI` when starting the webhook, or store it in the **Notes** JSON of your KSM config record (see project `README` → KSM-backed settings).
    10	
    11	### Optional: Vault record for webhook settings (KSM)
    12	
    13	Create a record **shared with your KSM application** used by this host. Put the **enterprise role ID** in the **Login** field (or set `KSM_FIELD_ROLE` to match your field type), optional **Password** for webhook bearer verification, and **Notes** as JSON for `pam_grant_seconds`, `keeper_cli`, `commander_dry_run`. Set `KSM_CONFIG_RECORD_UID` in `.env` to that record’s UID. Run `python scripts/bind_ksm.py` first so `ksm-config.json` exists.
    14	
    15	## 1. Enterprise role (time-bound PAM)
    16	
    17	1. Admin Console → **Roles** → create a role, e.g. `PAM-Session-1m`.
    18	2. Enable **KeeperPAM** / connection permissions per your policy (minimum needed for users to launch RBI sessions).
    19	3. Record the **role ID** (numeric or string as shown in Commander: `enterprise-role info` / Admin UI).
    20	
    21	Set `ENTERPRISE_ROLE_ID` on the webhook host to this value.
    22	
    23	## 2. Test users (3–5)
    24	
    25	```text
    26	create-user test1@yourdomain.com --name "Test One"
    27	```
    28	
    29	Repeat for each tester. **Do not** permanently add them to the PAM role; the webhook will add/remove.
    30	
    31	## 3. KSM application folders (if not already done)
    32	
    33	Ensure your KSM app has the shared folders it needs (see existing gateway/KSM docs). This project’s `bind_ksm.py` only binds the device; folder sharing is in Admin Console / Commander.
    34	
    35	## 4. PAM Configuration
    36	
    37	Link your **Gateway** to a **PAM Configuration** and an **application folder** (see PAM Configuration docs).
    38	
    39	## 5. PAM User (portal credentials)
    40	
    41	Create a **PAM User** record with the **username/password** for the target web app (test portal). Only admins (or automation) should manage this record.
    42	
    43	## 6. PAM Remote Browser (RBI)
    44	
    45	1. Create **PAM Remote Browser**; set target URL (any HTTPS demo login: internal app, httpbin basic-auth, etc.).
    46	2. **PAM Settings** → Connection → enable **Remote Browser Isolation**; set **PAM Configuration**; set **Administrative Credential Record** to the PAM User from step 5.
    47	3. Enable **Browser Autofill** if you want username/password filled in the isolated session.
    48	
    49	Recipients who only receive the **PAM Remote Browser** record do **not** get the linked admin credentials (see RBI docs).
    50	
    51	## 7. Share RBI record with testers
    52	
    53	Put the PAM Remote Browser record in a **shared folder** or share to a **team** that contains your test users.
    54	
    55	## 8. “Request access” record
    56	
    57	1. Create a normal **Login** or **Note** record: title e.g. “Enable PAM for 1 minute”.
    58	2. In the notes, instruct users to **open this record** (or use a vault deep link) before launching RBI, and optionally link to your public **`/status`** page.
    59	3. Deep link format (US commercial): `https://keepersecurity.com/vault/#detail/<RECORD_UID>` (adjust domain for EU/AU/CA/JP/GOV).
    60	
    61	## 9. Audit alert + webhook
    62	
    63	Requires **ARAM** (Advanced Reporting & Alerts) where applicable.
    64	
    65	1. Identify the **audit event** that fires when a user opens/views the record from step 8 (exact code depends on tenant; use Reporting UI or Commander `audit-report` to discover event types).
    66	2. Create an alert scoped to that **record UID** and event:
    67	
    68	   ```text
    69	   audit-alert add --name "PAM grant on request" --frequency event --audit-event <EVENT_CODE> --record-uid <REQUEST_RECORD_UID> --active on
    70	   ```
    71	
    72	3. Add a **webhook** recipient pointing to your public URL, e.g. `https://<tunnel-host>/keeper-webhook`.
    73	4. Optional: `audit-alert recipient <AlertName> add --webhook ... --generate-token` and set `WEBHOOK_BEARER_TOKEN` on the server.
    74	
    75	Webhook body should include user identity; Keeper supports template variables such as `#username` and `#json` (see Enterprise Webhooks documentation).
    76	
    77	## 10. Validate
    78	
    79	1. Set `COMMANDER_DRY_RUN=true`, trigger the alert, confirm webhook logs and `state.json`.
    80	2. Remove dry-run, confirm `enterprise-role` add/remove works on the webhook host.
    81	3. Open RBI record and confirm session works while the role is active.
    82	
    83	## Known gaps
    84	
    85	- **Event latency:** Some reporting paths can delay events; measure webhook delivery time in your tenant.
    86	- **Commander batch:** If `keeper enterprise-role ...` is not supported non-interactively, use a wrapper or run automation via a logged-in session pattern documented for your OS.

