     1	# KSM Bootstrap
     2	
     3	## What this does
     4	
     5	`dsk bootstrap-ksm` provisions the first Keeper Secrets Manager application for
     6	the SDK: it creates or reuses the KSM app, shares the Commander admin login
     7	record into that app, generates and redeems a client token, writes
     8	`ksm-config.json`, and verifies the resulting client can see the admin record.
     9	After that, use `KsmLoginHelper` as described in
    10	[`KSM_INTEGRATION.md`](./KSM_INTEGRATION.md).
    11	
    12	## Prerequisites
    13	
    14	- `keeper login` has authenticated the source admin Commander session.
    15	- The SDK was installed with KSM support:
    16	
    17	  ```bash
    18	  pip install 'declarative-sdk-for-k[ksm]'
    19	  ```
    20	
    21	- The authenticated Keeper account can create vault records, create KSM
    22	  applications, share records into KSM applications, and generate KSM clients.
    23	
    24	## Quickstart
    25	
    26	Use an existing admin login record:
    27	
    28	```bash
    29	dsk bootstrap-ksm \
    30	  --app-name dsk-service-admin \
    31	  --admin-record-uid <ADMIN_RECORD_UID> \
    32	  --config-out ~/.keeper/dsk-service-admin-ksm-config.json \
    33	  --first-access-minutes 10
    34	```
    35	
    36	Then enable the steady-state helper:
    37	
    38	```bash
    39	export KEEPER_SDK_LOGIN_HELPER=ksm
    40	export KEEPER_SDK_KSM_CREDS_RECORD_UID=<ADMIN_RECORD_UID>
    41	export KEEPER_SDK_KSM_CONFIG=~/.keeper/dsk-service-admin-ksm-config.json
    42	```
    43	
    44	Flag notes:
    45	
    46	- `--app-name` is the KSM application title. It must be 64 characters or fewer.
    47	- `--admin-record-uid` shares an existing login record into the app.
    48	- `--create-admin-record` creates a placeholder login/password/oneTimeCode
    49	  record instead; populate it in Keeper Web UI before using `KsmLoginHelper`.
    50	- `--config-out` chooses where the redeemed client config is written.
    51	- `--first-access-minutes` controls token first-access expiry. The token is
    52	  redeemed during bootstrap, so the timestamp is audit metadata after success.
    53	- `--unlock-ip` disables KSM IP locking for the new client.
    54	
    55	## Idempotent Re-bootstrap
    56	
    57	Reusing the same `--app-name` is supported. The command reuses an existing app
    58	with that title, shares the requested admin record, generates a fresh client,
    59	and writes a fresh config.
    60	
    61	Use `--overwrite` when replacing an existing config at the same `--config-out`
    62	path. Without it, the command refuses to overwrite the file.
    63	
    64	For token rotation planning, use a long-lived app plus short client lifetimes:
    65	set `--first-access-minutes 0` only when you intend to manage first access
    66	manually, then create future clients with Commander:
    67	
    68	```bash
    69	keeper secrets-manager client add <APP_UID>
    70	```
    71	
    72	## Bus
    73	
    74	`--with-bus` creates or reuses a vault record titled
    75	`dsk-agent-bus-directory` with a custom JSON field labelled `topics`. The record
    76	is shared into the KSM app with write access because the future bus will carry
    77	write traffic.
    78	
    79	The read/write/CAS library API for the bus is not shipped yet. Treat this as a
    80	Phase B preview hook.
    81	
    82	## Cleanup
    83	
    84	To undo a bootstrap, remove the KSM app and any records created only for the
    85	bootstrap:
    86	
    87	```bash
    88	keeper secrets-manager app remove <APP_UID>
    89	keeper rm <RECORD_UID>
    90	```
    91	
    92	Do not remove the existing admin login record unless you created it only for a
    93	discarded bootstrap.
    94	
    95	## Audit Trail
    96	
    97	Keeper Web UI Event Reporting shows the KSM application, share, client, and
    98	Secrets Manager access events under `secrets-manager` activity.
    99	
   100	## What This Does Not Do
   101	
   102	- It does not enrol TOTP for the admin record. The operator must populate or
   103	  enrol the record in Keeper Web UI.
   104	- It does not revoke prior KSM clients or tokens. Use Commander client revoke
   105	  workflows for that.
   106	- It does not rotate the admin password. Use the SDK rotation surface once that
   107	  workflow is GA.

